    <name>
      <text>28.2.1.5 grad normal and rate of change question</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>If \(\phi = {@express@},\) find,</p>

<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>\(\underline{\nabla} \phi =\)[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]\(\underline{i} + \)[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]\(\underline{j} + \)[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] \(\underline{k}\) [[feedback:prt1]]</li>

<li>a unit vector normal to the contour at the point \((1, 1, 1)\): [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] \(\underline{i} + \)[[input:ans5]]  [[validation:ans5]] \(\underline{j} + \)[[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] \(\underline{k}\) [[feedback:prt2]]</li>

<li>the rate of change of \(\phi\) at \((1, 1, 1)\) in the direction of \(\underline{i}\): [[input:ans7]][[validation:ans7]] [[feedback:prt3]]</li>

<li>the rate of change of \(\phi\) at \((1, 1, 1)\) in the direction of the unit vector \(\underline{n} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\underline{i}+\underline{j}+\underline{k})\): [[input:ans8]][[validation:ans8]] [[feedback:prt4]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>For  \(\phi = {@express@},\) we find,</p>

<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>\(\underline{\nabla} \phi = \dfrac{\partial \phi}{\partial x} \underline{i} + \dfrac{\partial \phi}{\partial y} \underline{j} + \dfrac{\partial \phi}{\partial z} \underline{k} = {@ta1i@} \underline{i} + {@ta1j@} \underline{j} + {@ta1k@}\underline{k}\)</li>

<li><p>The vector normal to a contour at a point is the same as \(\underline{\nabla} \phi\) at that point. To make this a normal vector, we then divide by the vector's magnitude \(|\underline{\nabla} \phi|\).</p>
<p>In this case, we find that at \((1,1,1)\) the \(\underline{\nabla} \phi = {@feedvar1@}\underline{i} + {@feedvar2@}\underline{j} + {@feedvar3@}\underline{k} = {@feedvar4@}\underline{i} + {@feedvar5@}\underline{j} + {@feedvar6@}\underline{k}.\)</p>
<p>The magnitude of this vector is then \(|\underline{\nabla} \phi| = \sqrt{{@feedvar4@}^2 + {@feedvar5@}^2 + {@feedvar6@}^2} ={@exp_at_point_magnitude@}\).</p>
<p>This gives a final answer for the  unit vector normal to the contour at the point \((1, 1, 1)\) as: \({@ta2i@}\underline{i} + {@ta2j@}\underline{j} + {@ta2k@} \underline{k}\).</p></li>

<li>We note that the change in a function \(\phi\) in a given direction (specified as a unit vector \(\underline{a} \)) is determined from the scalar product \((\underline{\nabla}\phi)\cdot \underline{a}\).</p>
<p>In this case, for \(\underline{a} = \underline{i}\) at the point \((1, 1, 1)\), we find that \((\underline{\nabla}\phi)\cdot \underline{a} =  \dfrac{\partial \phi}{\partial x} \underline{i} = {@ta3@}\).</li>

<li><p>Similarly to the previous question, for \(\underline{a} = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k})\) at the point \((1, 1, 1)\), we find that \((\underline{\nabla}\phi)\cdot \underline{a} =({@sub_point_fun(ta1i)@} \underline{i} + {@sub_point_fun(ta1j)@} \underline{j} + {@sub_point_fun(ta1k)@}\underline{k}) \cdot \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(\underline{i} + \underline{j} + \underline{k}) = {@ta4@}\).</p></li>
</ol>]]></text>
